[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 7.1: Appointment No-Show Prediction ⭐
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    3,   3[0m:[39m[49m **Complexity:** Simple · **Phase:** MVP · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.001 per prediction
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m Here's a number that should make any clinic operations manager wince: somewhere between 5% and 30% of scheduled outpatient appointments end up as no-shows. The patient just doesn't come. No call, no cancellation, no reschedule. The slot sits empty.
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m That empty slot isn't free. A primary care physician's time is worth roughly $200-400 per hour, depending on specialty and market. A 15-minute slot that goes unused is $50-100 of lost revenue. Multiply that across a 20-provider practice with a 15% no-show rate, and you're looking at hundreds of thousands of dollars in annual lost revenue. For a large health system with hundreds of providers, the number crosses into the millions.
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m But the financial hit is only part of the story. That empty slot could have gone to another patient. Someone who needed to be seen. Someone on a waitlist. Someone whose condition is getting worse while they wait three weeks for the next available appointment. No-shows don't just cost money; they cost access.
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m The standard response has been blunt-force overbooking: schedule 110% of capacity and hope the math works out. Sometimes it does. Sometimes three patients all show up for two slots and the waiting room turns hostile. Overbooking without intelligence is a gamble, and the downside is a terrible patient experience for the people who did show up on time.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m What if you could predict which specific appointments are likely to no-show? Not "15% of Tuesday afternoon appointments" as a population average, but "this specific appointment with this specific patient has a 73% chance of being missed." That changes everything. You can send targeted reminders to high-risk appointments. You can selectively overbook only the slots most likely to open up. You can offer waitlisted patients those specific slots as standby options. You can allocate staff time toward outreach rather than hoping for the best.
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m This is one of the cleanest prediction problems in healthcare operations. Binary outcome (showed vs. didn't show). Abundant historical data (every scheduling system has years of it). Low-stakes intervention (a reminder call or text). And the feedback loop is immediate: you find out within hours whether your prediction was right.
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m Let's build it.
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: Predicting Human Behavior from Patterns
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m ### Binary Classification: The Foundation
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m At its core, no-show prediction is a binary classification problem. Given a set of features about an upcoming appointment, predict one of two outcomes: the patient will show up, or they won't. This is the bread and butter of machine learning, and it's been well-understood for decades.
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m The simplest version is logistic regression: a mathematical function that takes a weighted combination of input features and squishes the result into a probability between 0 and 1. If the output is 0.73, you interpret that as "73% chance of no-show." It's interpretable, fast, and surprisingly effective for this problem. Many production no-show models in healthcare are still logistic regression under the hood, because the features matter more than the algorithm.
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m Gradient-boosted trees (XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost) are the next step up. They build an ensemble of decision trees, each one correcting the errors of the previous ones. They handle non-linear relationships, feature interactions, and missing values more gracefully than logistic regression. For tabular data like appointment records, they're typically the best-performing approach without requiring deep learning infrastructure.
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m Deep learning (neural networks) is overkill for this problem in most cases. The data is tabular, the feature space is modest, and the relationship between features and outcome isn't complex enough to justify the training overhead. Save neural networks for problems where you have unstructured data (images, text, sequences) or millions of training examples with subtle patterns.
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m ### The Features That Actually Matter
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m Here's what decades of no-show research have consistently found to be predictive:
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m **Patient history.** The single strongest predictor of a future no-show is past no-shows. A patient who has missed 4 of their last 10 appointments has a dramatically higher probability of missing the next one than a patient with a perfect attendance record. This is the "prior behavior predicts future behavior" principle, and it dominates most models.
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m **Lead time.** The gap between when the appointment was scheduled and when it's supposed to happen. An appointment booked 6 weeks out has a much higher no-show rate than one booked 2 days out. This makes intuitive sense: life changes, people forget, the urgency that prompted the booking fades.
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m **Day and time.** Monday mornings and Friday afternoons tend to have higher no-show rates. So do appointments during school hours for pediatric patients. These patterns are highly local to your specific practice and patient population.
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m **Appointment type.** Follow-up visits no-show at higher rates than new patient visits. Routine wellness checks no-show more than urgent symptom visits. The perceived urgency of the visit matters.
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m **Demographics and access factors.** Distance from the clinic, transportation access, insurance type (Medicaid populations historically show higher no-show rates, reflecting access barriers, not irresponsibility), age, and language barriers all correlate with no-show probability. These features improve accuracy but require careful handling to avoid reinforcing disparities (more on this in the Honest Take section).
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m **Weather and external events.** Rain, snow, extreme heat, and local events (school closures, major sports events) all measurably affect no-show rates. These are harder to incorporate because they require external data sources and real-time feature computation, but they can add a few percentage points of accuracy.
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m **Reminder history.** Whether the patient has already received a reminder, and whether they confirmed. A patient who confirmed via text 24 hours ago is much less likely to no-show than one who hasn't responded to any outreach.
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m ### Why This Is Easier Than Most Healthcare ML
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m No-show prediction has several properties that make it unusually tractable:
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m **Clear, objective outcome.** The patient either showed up or didn't. There's no ambiguity, no subjective labeling, no inter-rater disagreement. Your training labels are clean.
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m **Abundant data.** Any scheduling system with 2+ years of history has tens of thousands of labeled examples. You don't need to go find data or label it manually. It's already there.
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m **Fast feedback loop.** You know the outcome within hours of the prediction. This means you can retrain frequently, detect model drift quickly, and measure your accuracy in near-real-time.
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m **Low-stakes intervention.** If your model says "high risk of no-show" and you send an extra reminder, the worst case is a mildly annoyed patient who was going to show up anyway. Compare that to a model that recommends a medication or a surgical intervention. The cost of a false positive here is a text message.
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m **No regulatory burden.** This isn't a clinical decision support tool. It's an operational optimization. You don't need FDA clearance, you don't need clinical validation studies, and you don't need physician sign-off on the model's recommendations. (You do still need to handle PHI appropriately, but that's table stakes in healthcare.)
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m The pipeline has four logical stages:
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m [Feature Store] → [Model Training] → [Scoring Service] → [Action Engine]
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m **Feature Store.** A pre-computed repository of patient and appointment features, updated on a schedule. Raw data from your scheduling system, EHR, and demographics tables gets transformed into model-ready features: no-show rate over the last N appointments, days since last visit, distance to clinic, appointment lead time, and so on. Computing these on the fly at prediction time is possible but slow and fragile. A feature store decouples feature engineering from model serving.
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m **Model Training.** A batch process that trains (or retrains) the classification model on historical appointment data. Runs on a schedule (weekly or monthly) or when triggered by performance degradation. Outputs a serialized model artifact and a performance report (AUC, calibration curve, feature importance).
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m **Scoring Service.** An inference endpoint that accepts an appointment's features and returns a no-show probability. This runs in near-real-time: when a new appointment is booked, or on a nightly batch for the next day's schedule. The output is a probability (0.0 to 1.0) and optionally the top contributing features (for explainability).
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m **Action Engine.** The system that decides what to do with the prediction. Above a certain threshold, trigger an extra reminder. Above a higher threshold, flag the slot for overbooking consideration. Below the threshold, do nothing special. The thresholds are operational decisions, not model decisions. They depend on your reminder capacity, your overbooking tolerance, and your patient experience goals.
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m This separation of concerns is important. The model predicts. The action engine decides. Changing your reminder strategy shouldn't require retraining the model, and improving the model shouldn't require changing your operational workflows.
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and hosting.** SageMaker handles the infrastructure you don't want to manage: spinning up a training instance, running the XGBoost job, storing the model artifact, and tearing everything down when it's done. For tabular classification problems like no-show prediction, the built-in XGBoost algorithm is a strong default. The batch transform mode is particularly useful here: score tomorrow's entire schedule in one job rather than standing up a persistent endpoint that sits idle 23 hours a day.
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon S3 for data and model storage.** Training data (historical appointments with outcomes), feature datasets, and trained model artifacts all live in S3. It's the natural staging area between your data warehouse and SageMaker, and between SageMaker and your inference pipeline. Versioned buckets let you track which training data produced which model.
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Glue for feature engineering.** The ETL layer that transforms raw scheduling data into model-ready features. Glue jobs can pull from your data warehouse (Redshift, RDS, or wherever your scheduling system stores data), compute derived features (rolling no-show rates, lead time calculations, distance computations), and write the results to S3 in a format SageMaker can consume. Scheduled Glue jobs keep your feature store fresh.
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for orchestration.** Triggers the nightly scoring pipeline: "At 8 PM, score all appointments for the next 48 hours." Also triggers retraining on a schedule or when a CloudWatch alarm fires on model performance degradation.
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for prediction storage.** Scored predictions need to be accessible to downstream systems (your scheduling UI, your reminder engine, your overbooking logic). DynamoDB provides fast key-value lookups by appointment ID with low latency. The reminder engine queries "give me all appointments in the next 24 hours with no-show probability > 0.6" and acts on them.
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  103, 103[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Lambda for the action engine.** Lightweight functions that read predictions from DynamoDB and trigger interventions: send a reminder via SNS/SES, flag a slot in the scheduling system, notify the front desk. Lambda's event-driven model fits naturally: a DynamoDB stream or EventBridge schedule triggers the appropriate action based on the prediction score and your configured thresholds.
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  108, 108[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[39m  109, 109[0m:[39m[49m     A[Scheduling System\nEHR / PM System] -->|Nightly Extract| B[AWS Glue\nFeature Engineering]
[0m[49m[39m  110, 110[0m:[39m[49m     B -->|Feature Dataset| C[S3 Bucket\nfeatures/]
[0m[49m[39m  111, 111[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Training Data| D[SageMaker\nTraining Job]
[0m[49m[39m  112, 112[0m:[39m[49m     D -->|Model Artifact| E[S3 Bucket\nmodels/]
[0m[49m[39m  113, 113[0m:[39m[49m     E -->|Deploy| F[SageMaker\nBatch Transform]
[0m[49m[39m  114, 114[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Scoring Input| F
[0m[49m[39m  115, 115[0m:[39m[49m     F -->|Predictions| G[DynamoDB\nappointment-predictions]
[0m[49m[39m  116, 116[0m:[39m[49m     H[EventBridge\nNightly Schedule] -->|Trigger| F
[0m[49m[39m  117, 117[0m:[39m[49m     H -->|Trigger| I[Lambda\nAction Engine]
[0m[49m[39m  118, 118[0m:[39m[49m     G -->|Read Predictions| I
[0m[49m[39m  119, 119[0m:[39m[49m     I -->|High-Risk| J[SNS / SES\nReminder Service]
[0m[49m[39m  120, 120[0m:[39m[49m     I -->|Flag Slot| K[Scheduling System\nOverbook Queue]
[0m[49m[39m  121, 121[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  122, 122[0m:[39m[49m     style D fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  123, 123[0m:[39m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  124, 124[0m:[39m[49m     style G fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  125, 125[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  126, 126[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  127, 127[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  128, 128[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  129, 129[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Lambda, Amazon EventBridge, Amazon SNS or SES |
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | Distributed across service-specific roles: Glue execution role (S3 read/write on feature buckets, data source access); SageMaker execution role (S3 read/write on model/feature buckets, KMS decrypt); Lambda action engine role (DynamoDB read, SNS publish); EventBridge scheduler role (Lambda invoke, SageMaker transform). Scope each role to specific resource ARNs. The Lambda role should NOT have SageMaker or Glue permissions. |
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (appointment data contains PHI: patient names, dates of birth, contact info) |
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for training data and model artifacts; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default), TTL enabled to expire predictions after appointment date + 90 days (PHI retention policy); SageMaker: KMS-encrypted training volumes and endpoints; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker training and inference in VPC with gateway endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB. Additional interface endpoints required: SageMaker API, SNS, CloudWatch Logs, and KMS. Glue jobs in VPC with access to data sources. |
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all SageMaker, S3, and DynamoDB API calls for audit |
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic appointment records. Generate from realistic distributions: 15% base no-show rate, correlated with lead time and patient history. Never use real patient data in dev. |
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | SageMaker training: ~$5-20 per training run (ml.m5.xlarge, 1-2 hours). Batch transform: ~$2-5 per nightly scoring run. DynamoDB: negligible at appointment volumes. Total: ~$200-500/month for a mid-size practice. |
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  140, 140[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  141, 141[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  142, 142[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  143, 143[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  144, 144[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Train XGBoost model on historical data; batch-score upcoming appointments |
[0m[49m[39m  145, 145[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Store training datasets, feature files, and model artifacts |
[0m[49m[39m  146, 146[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL: transform raw scheduling data into model-ready features |
[0m[49m[39m  147, 147[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Store predictions for fast lookup by appointment ID or date range |
[0m[49m[39m  148, 148[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Orchestrate nightly scoring and periodic retraining |
[0m[49m[39m  149, 149[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Action engine: read predictions, trigger reminders or overbooking flags |
[0m[49m[39m  150, 150[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SNS/SES** | Deliver reminder messages (SMS via SNS, email via SES) |
[0m[49m[39m  151, 151[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitor model performance, prediction distributions, and pipeline health |
[0m[49m[39m  152, 152[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  153, 153[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  154, 154[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  155, 155[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  156, 156[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  157, 157[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Feature engineering.** The Glue job runs nightly, pulling the latest appointment and patient data from your scheduling system. For each upcoming appointment, it computes the features the model needs: the patient's historical no-show rate, the lead time in days, the day of week, the appointment type, and demographic factors. It also pulls the outcome labels for recent past appointments (to feed retraining). The output is a clean CSV or Parquet file in S3, one row per appointment, ready for the model. Skip this step and you're asking the model to work with raw database records that have no predictive signal computed.
[0m[49m[39m  158, 158[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  159, 159[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  160, 160[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION compute_features(appointments, patient_history):
[0m[49m[39m  161, 161[0m:[39m[49m     // For each upcoming appointment, compute the feature vector
[0m[49m[39m  162, 162[0m:[39m[49m     // that the model needs to make a prediction.
[0m[49m[39m  163, 163[0m:[39m[49m     features = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  164, 164[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  165, 165[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each appointment in appointments:
[0m[49m[39m  166, 166[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id   = appointment.patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  167, 167[0m:[39m[49m         history      = patient_history[patient_id]
[0m[49m[39m  168, 168[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  169, 169[0m:[39m[49m         // The single most predictive feature: how often has this patient
[0m[49m[39m  170, 170[0m:[39m[49m         // no-showed in the past? Compute over their last 10 appointments
[0m[49m[39m  171, 171[0m:[39m[49m         // (or fewer if they're newer to the practice).
[0m[49m[39m  172, 172[0m:[39m[49m         past_appointments = history.last_n_appointments(10)
[0m[49m[39m  173, 173[0m:[39m[49m         no_show_rate = count(past_appointments where status = "NO_SHOW") / count(past_appointments)
[0m[49m[39m  174, 174[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  175, 175[0m:[39m[49m         // Lead time: days between booking date and appointment date.
[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m         // Longer lead times correlate strongly with higher no-show rates.
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m         lead_time_days = days_between(appointment.booked_date, appointment.scheduled_date)
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m         // Temporal features: day of week and hour of day both matter.
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m         // Monday mornings and Friday afternoons are historically worse.
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m         day_of_week = appointment.scheduled_date.day_of_week   // 0=Monday, 6=Sunday
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m         hour_of_day = appointment.scheduled_time.hour          // 0-23
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m         // Appointment characteristics
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m         visit_type     = encode_category(appointment.visit_type)   // "new", "follow_up", "wellness", "urgent"
[0m[49m[39m  186, 186[0m:[39m[49m         provider_id    = encode_category(appointment.provider_id)  // some providers have higher no-show rates
[0m[49m[39m  187, 187[0m:[39m[49m         department     = encode_category(appointment.department)
[0m[49m[39m  188, 188[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  189, 189[0m:[39m[49m         // Patient demographics and access factors
[0m[49m[39m  190, 190[0m:[39m[49m         distance_miles = compute_distance(patient.address, clinic.address)
[0m[49m[39m  191, 191[0m:[39m[49m         // NOTE: If distance computation requires an external geocoding API,
[0m[49m[39m  192, 192[0m:[39m[49m         // route through a NAT gateway with a BAA-covered provider, or
[0m[49m[39m  193, 193[0m:[39m[49m         // pre-geocode addresses at patient registration time to avoid
[0m[49m[39m  194, 194[0m:[39m[49m         // runtime PHI egress from this pipeline.
[0m[49m[39m  195, 195[0m:[39m[49m         insurance_type = encode_category(patient.insurance_type)   // "commercial", "medicaid", "medicare", "self_pay"
[0m[49m[39m  196, 196[0m:[39m[49m         age            = years_between(patient.date_of_birth, today)
[0m[49m[39m  197, 197[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m         // Recency: days since last completed visit.
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m         // Patients who haven't been seen in a long time are higher risk.
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m         days_since_last_visit = days_between(history.last_completed_visit_date, today)
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m         // Assemble the feature vector
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m         feature_row = {
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m             appointment_id:       appointment.id,
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m             no_show_rate_last_10: no_show_rate,
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m             lead_time_days:       lead_time_days,
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m             day_of_week:          day_of_week,
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m             hour_of_day:          hour_of_day,
[0m[49m[39m  209, 209[0m:[39m[49m             visit_type:           visit_type,
[0m[49m[39m  210, 210[0m:[39m[49m             provider_id:          provider_id,
[0m[49m[39m  211, 211[0m:[39m[49m             department:           department,
[0m[49m[39m  212, 212[0m:[39m[49m             distance_miles:       distance_miles,
[0m[49m[39m  213, 213[0m:[39m[49m             insurance_type:       insurance_type,
[0m[49m[39m  214, 214[0m:[39m[49m             age:                  age,
[0m[49m[39m  215, 215[0m:[39m[49m             days_since_last_visit: days_since_last_visit
[0m[49m[39m  216, 216[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  217, 217[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  218, 218[0m:[39m[49m         append feature_row to features
[0m[49m[39m  219, 219[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  220, 220[0m:[39m[49m     // Write to S3 as a Parquet file for SageMaker to consume
[0m[49m[39m  221, 221[0m:[39m[49m     write features to S3 at "s3://ml-data/features/upcoming/{date}.parquet"
[0m[49m[39m  222, 222[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[39m  223, 223[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  224, 224[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  225, 225[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Model training.** Periodically (weekly or monthly), a SageMaker training job picks up the historical feature dataset (appointments with known outcomes) and trains a gradient-boosted tree classifier. The training job handles hyperparameter tuning, cross-validation, and outputs both the model artifact and an evaluation report. The key metrics to track are AUC-ROC (overall discrimination ability), calibration (does a predicted 0.7 actually mean 70% no-show?), and performance across subgroups (does the model work equally well for different patient populations?). Skip retraining and your model will drift as patient behavior and scheduling patterns change over time.
[0m[49m[39m  226, 226[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  227, 227[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  228, 228[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION train_model(training_data_path):
[0m[49m[39m  229, 229[0m:[39m[49m     // Configure the SageMaker training job.
[0m[49m[39m  230, 230[0m:[39m[49m     // XGBoost is the right choice for tabular binary classification:
[0m[49m[39m  231, 231[0m:[39m[49m     // handles missing values, captures non-linear relationships,
[0m[49m[39m  232, 232[0m:[39m[49m     // and trains fast on modest data sizes.
[0m[49m[39m  233, 233[0m:[39m[49m     training_config = {
[0m[49m[39m  234, 234[0m:[39m[49m         algorithm:       "xgboost",
[0m[49m[39m  235, 235[0m:[39m[49m         objective:       "binary:logistic",    // output probabilities, not just 0/1
[0m[49m[39m  236, 236[0m:[39m[49m         eval_metric:     "auc",                // optimize for discrimination ability
[0m[49m[39m  237, 237[0m:[39m[49m         num_round:       200,                  // number of boosting rounds
[0m[49m[39m  238, 238[0m:[39m[49m         max_depth:       6,                    // tree depth (controls complexity)
[0m[49m[39m  239, 239[0m:[39m[49m         eta:             0.1,                  // learning rate (smaller = more conservative)
[0m[49m[39m  240, 240[0m:[39m[49m         subsample:       0.8,                  // use 80% of data per tree (reduces overfitting)
[0m[49m[39m  241, 241[0m:[39m[49m         colsample_bytree: 0.8,                // use 80% of features per tree
[0m[49m[39m  242, 242[0m:[39m[49m         scale_pos_weight: 5.5,                // adjust for class imbalance
[0m[49m[39m  243, 243[0m:[39m[49m                                               // Compute from YOUR training data:
[0m[49m[39m  244, 244[0m:[39m[49m                                               // count(showed) / count(no-showed).
[0m[49m[39m  245, 245[0m:[39m[49m                                               // 5.5 assumes ~15% no-show rate (85/15 ≈ 5.5).
[0m[49m[39m  246, 246[0m:[39m[49m                                               // A 25% rate needs ~3.0; a 7% rate needs ~13.
[0m[49m[39m  247, 247[0m:[39m[49m                                               // Recompute on each retrain as distribution shifts.
[0m[49m[39m  248, 248[0m:[39m[49m         input_data:      training_data_path,
[0m[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m         output_path:     "s3://ml-data/models/no-show/",
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m         instance_type:   "ml.m5.xlarge",      // sufficient for datasets under 1M rows
[0m[49m[39m  251, 251[0m:[39m[49m         instance_count:  1
[0m[49m[39m  252, 252[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  253, 253[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  254, 254[0m:[39m[49m     // Launch the training job. SageMaker handles provisioning,
[0m[49m[39m  255, 255[0m:[39m[49m     // training, evaluation, and artifact storage.
[0m[49m[39m  256, 256[0m:[39m[49m     job = SageMaker.create_training_job(training_config)
[0m[49m[39m  257, 257[0m:[39m[49m     wait_for_completion(job)
[0m[49m[39m  258, 258[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  259, 259[0m:[39m[49m     // Log the evaluation metrics for monitoring
[0m[49m[39m  260, 260[0m:[39m[49m     metrics = job.final_metrics   // AUC, accuracy, log loss
[0m[49m[39m  261, 261[0m:[39m[49m     log("Model trained. AUC: {metrics.auc}, LogLoss: {metrics.log_loss}")
[0m[49m[39m  262, 262[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  263, 263[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN job.model_artifact_path
[0m[49m[39m  264, 264[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  265, 265[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  266, 266[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Batch scoring.** Every evening, a SageMaker batch transform job scores all appointments for the next 48 hours. Batch transform is more cost-effective than a persistent endpoint for this use case: you need predictions once per day, not continuously. The job reads the feature file from Step 1, applies the trained model, and outputs a prediction for each appointment. Each prediction is a probability between 0.0 and 1.0 representing the model's estimate of no-show likelihood.
[0m[49m[39m  267, 267[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  268, 268[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  269, 269[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION score_upcoming_appointments(model_path, features_path):
[0m[49m[39m  270, 270[0m:[39m[49m     // Configure batch transform: apply the model to all upcoming appointments at once.
[0m[49m[39m  271, 271[0m:[39m[49m     // This is cheaper than a real-time endpoint when you only need predictions once daily.
[0m[49m[39m  272, 272[0m:[39m[49m     transform_config = {
[0m[49m[39m  273, 273[0m:[39m[49m         model_artifact:  model_path,
[0m[49m[39m  274, 274[0m:[39m[49m         input_data:      features_path,                          // today's feature file from Step 1
[0m[49m[39m  275, 275[0m:[39m[49m         output_path:     "s3://ml-data/predictions/{date}/",     // predictions land here
[0m[49m[39m  276, 276[0m:[39m[49m         instance_type:   "ml.m5.large",                          // sufficient for scoring
[0m[49m[39m  277, 277[0m:[39m[49m         instance_count:  1,
[0m[49m[39m  278, 278[0m:[39m[49m         content_type:    "text/csv",
[0m[49m[39m  279, 279[0m:[39m[49m         split_type:      "Line",                                 // one prediction per input row
[0m[49m[39m  280, 280[0m:[39m[49m         network_isolation: true                                   // defense-in-depth: container has no
[0m[49m[39m  281, 281[0m:[39m[49m                                                                  // outbound network access (reads/writes
[0m[49m[39m  282, 282[0m:[39m[49m                                                                  // via SageMaker-managed S3 channels only)
[0m[49m[39m  283, 283[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  284, 284[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  285, 285[0m:[39m[49m     job = SageMaker.create_transform_job(transform_config)
[0m[49m[39m  286, 286[0m:[39m[49m     wait_for_completion(job)
[0m[49m[39m  287, 287[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  288, 288[0m:[39m[49m     // Read predictions and pair them with appointment IDs.
[0m[49m[39m  289, 289[0m:[39m[49m     // Batch transform output is positional: line N of the output file
[0m[49m[39m  290, 290[0m:[39m[49m     // contains the prediction for line N of the input file.
[0m[49m[39m  291, 291[0m:[39m[49m     // Join predictions back to appointment IDs by index position.
[0m[49m[39m  292, 292[0m:[39m[49m     predictions = read_predictions(transform_config.output_path)
[0m[49m[39m  293, 293[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN predictions   // list of {appointment_id, no_show_probability}
[0m[49m[39m  294, 294[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  295, 295[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  296, 296[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Store predictions.** Write each prediction to DynamoDB so downstream systems can look them up quickly. The primary key is the appointment ID; a secondary index on scheduled date enables range queries like "all high-risk appointments for tomorrow." Each record includes the probability, the model version (for auditability), and a timestamp. This step bridges the ML pipeline and the operational systems. Without it, predictions exist only as a file in S3 that nothing can easily query.
[0m[49m[39m  297, 297[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  298, 298[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A3 (MEDIUM). Add conditional write guidance to prevent overwriting predictions already acted upon. Use condition expression `attribute_not_exists(acted_at)` or append a pipeline_run_id for audit consistency between predictions and actions. -->
[0m[49m[39m  299, 299[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  300, 300[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  301, 301[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_predictions(predictions):
[0m[49m[39m  302, 302[0m:[39m[49m     // Write each prediction to DynamoDB for fast downstream access.
[0m[49m[39m  303, 303[0m:[39m[49m     // The action engine and scheduling UI both read from this table.
[0m[49m[39m  304, 304[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each prediction in predictions:
[0m[49m[39m  305, 305[0m:[39m[49m         write to DynamoDB table "appointment-predictions":
[0m[49m[39m  306, 306[0m:[39m[49m             appointment_id     = prediction.appointment_id       // primary key
[0m[49m[39m  307, 307[0m:[39m[49m             scheduled_date     = prediction.scheduled_date       // sort key + GSI for date queries
[0m[49m[39m  308, 308[0m:[39m[49m             no_show_probability = prediction.probability         // 0.0 to 1.0
[0m[49m[39m  309, 309[0m:[39m[49m             risk_tier          = classify_risk(prediction.probability)  // "low", "medium", "high"
[0m[49m[39m  310, 310[0m:[39m[49m             model_version      = current_model_version           // which model produced this
[0m[49m[39m  311, 311[0m:[39m[49m             scored_at          = current UTC timestamp           // when the prediction was made
[0m[49m[39m  312, 312[0m:[39m[49m             features_used      = prediction.top_features         // top 3 contributing features
[0m[49m[39m  313, 313[0m:[39m[49m                                                                  // (for explainability in the UI)
[0m[49m[39m  314, 314[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  315, 315[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION classify_risk(probability):
[0m[49m[39m  316, 316[0m:[39m[49m     // Convert continuous probability into actionable tiers.
[0m[49m[39m  317, 317[0m:[39m[49m     // Thresholds are operational decisions, not model decisions.
[0m[49m[39m  318, 318[0m:[39m[49m     // Tune these based on your reminder capacity and tolerance for false positives.
[0m[49m[39m  319, 319[0m:[39m[49m     IF probability >= 0.7:  RETURN "high"      // aggressive intervention
[0m[49m[39m  320, 320[0m:[39m[49m     IF probability >= 0.4:  RETURN "medium"    // standard reminder
[0m[49m[39m  321, 321[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN "low"                                // no special action
[0m[49m[39m  322, 322[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  323, 323[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  324, 324[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Action engine.** A Lambda function, triggered by EventBridge on a schedule (e.g., every morning at 6 AM for that day's appointments, and again at 6 PM for the next day's), queries DynamoDB for high-risk appointments and triggers the appropriate intervention. The intervention depends on the risk tier and your operational capacity. High-risk appointments might get a personal phone call from staff. Medium-risk gets an automated text reminder. Low-risk gets the standard reminder workflow (which you probably already have). The key insight: this is where the prediction becomes action. A model that scores perfectly but never triggers an intervention is worthless.
[0m[49m[39m  325, 325[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  326, 326[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  327, 327[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION run_action_engine(target_date):
[0m[49m[39m  328, 328[0m:[39m[49m     // Query all predictions for the target date, filtered to actionable risk levels.
[0m[49m[39m  329, 329[0m:[39m[49m     high_risk = query DynamoDB "appointment-predictions"
[0m[49m[39m  330, 330[0m:[39m[49m                 WHERE scheduled_date = target_date
[0m[49m[39m  331, 331[0m:[39m[49m                 AND risk_tier = "high"
[0m[49m[39m  332, 332[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  333, 333[0m:[39m[49m     medium_risk = query DynamoDB "appointment-predictions"
[0m[49m[39m  334, 334[0m:[39m[49m                   WHERE scheduled_date = target_date
[0m[49m[39m  335, 335[0m:[39m[49m                   AND risk_tier = "medium"
[0m[49m[39m  336, 336[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  337, 337[0m:[39m[49m     // High-risk: aggressive intervention
[0m[49m[39m  338, 338[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each appointment in high_risk:
[0m[49m[39m  339, 339[0m:[39m[49m         // Send personalized reminder with easy reschedule option.
[0m[49m[39m  340, 340[0m:[39m[49m         // Keep SMS content minimal: date/time and a generic prompt only.
[0m[49m[39m  341, 341[0m:[39m[49m         // Do not include provider name, visit type, or clinical details in SMS.
[0m[49m[39m  342, 342[0m:[39m[49m         // SMS is not encrypted end-to-end; link to a secure portal for specifics.
[0m[49m[39m  343, 343[0m:[39m[49m         send_reminder(
[0m[49m[39m  344, 344[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id:  appointment.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  345, 345[0m:[39m[49m             channel:     "sms",                          // SMS has highest open rates
[0m[49m[39m  346, 346[0m:[39m[49m             message:     personalized_reminder(appointment),
[0m[49m[39m  347, 347[0m:[39m[49m             include_reschedule_link: true                 // make it easy to reschedule rather than no-show
[0m[49m[39m  348, 348[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  349, 349[0m:[39m[49m         // Flag for potential overbooking
[0m[49m[39m  350, 350[0m:[39m[49m         flag_for_overbooking(appointment.slot_id)
[0m[49m[39m  351, 351[0m:[39m[49m         // Notify front desk for personal outreach if capacity allows
[0m[49m[39m  352, 352[0m:[39m[49m         notify_staff(appointment, reason="high no-show risk")
[0m[49m[39m  353, 353[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  354, 354[0m:[39m[49m     // Medium-risk: automated reminder (supplement standard workflow)
[0m[49m[39m  355, 355[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each appointment in medium_risk:
[0m[49m[39m  356, 356[0m:[39m[49m         send_reminder(
[0m[49m[39m  357, 357[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id:  appointment.patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  358, 358[0m:[39m[49m             channel:     "sms",
[0m[49m[39m  359, 359[0m:[39m[49m             message:     standard_reminder(appointment),
[0m[49m[39m  360, 360[0m:[39m[49m             include_reschedule_link: true
[0m[49m[39m  361, 361[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  362, 362[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  363, 363[0m:[39m[49m     log("Actions triggered: {count(high_risk)} high-risk, {count(medium_risk)} medium-risk")
[0m[49m[39m  364, 364[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  365, 365[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  366, 366[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter07.01-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  367, 367[0m:[39m[49m 
